comments.author: Sam Sim

comments.text:
I think there is a mistake in the math discussed here. It seems they 
calculated the total quantum states pertaining to 10^80 particles.

Now if the universe was googol meters across with only 10^80 particles, 
there would not be enough particles to create all the possible quantum 
states (even though the size of the universe would allow it). Most likely 
this event will lead to the "heat death of the universe, where the 
temperature of the entire universe would be stable at -273K and no energy 
exchange would be possible hence the universe would be dormant.

However, if the number of particles also increases in proportion to the 
size of the universe, then the total quantum states would also explode and 
would be unimaginable larger than what they calculated (10^10^70).

In fact, the size of universe classically thought (15 billion light years 
across) is only the observable universe, and the entire space could 
actually be infinite meaning an infinite universe right now (much larger 
than googolplex)﻿
